{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480086","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480086"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:36:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:36:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.21,0.46,0.16,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75423"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60933"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"3996"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7117"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2657"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3682"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35800"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75423"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 51-year-old man presents to the Neurosurgery clinic for consideration of surgery for drug-resistant epilepsy. He has a five-year history of focal seizures that have not responded to three different anti-epileptic medications. He has no other significant medical history. His current medications are levetiracetam, carbamazepine and lamotrigine. He works as an accountant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination is normal. After review of his imaging and electroencephalogram findings, he is offered anterior temporal lobectomy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following visual field deficits is most likely to occur following this procedure?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bitemporal hemianopia","Homonymous hemianopia","Superior quadrantanopia","Inferior quadrantanopia","Ipsilateral monocular blindness"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is being considered for anterior temporal lobectomy, which is an established surgical treatment for drug-resistant temporal lobe epilepsy. The inferior optic radiation, also known as Meyer\u0027s loop, courses through the anterior temporal lobe. Therefore, surgical resection in this area can result in a contralateral \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior quadrantanopia\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInferior quadrantanopia\u003C/strong\u003E results from damage to the superior optic radiations in the parietal lobe, which would not be affected by temporal lobe surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBitemporal hemianopia\u003C/strong\u003E occurs with damage to the optic chiasm, typically from lesions such as pituitary tumours that compress the crossing fibres.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHomonymous hemianopia\u003C/strong\u003E results from complete interruption of the retrochiasmal visual pathway, which would be more extensive than the deficit expected from a focal temporal lobe resection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIpsilateral monocular blindness\u003C/strong\u003E occurs with damage to the optic nerve or eye, which are not involved in temporal lobe surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe risk of visual field deficits after temporal lobe surgery is significant, occurring in up to 40% of patients. However, most patients consider this an acceptable risk given the potential benefits of seizure freedom. Careful surgical technique and preoperative mapping can help minimise the extent of visual field loss.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Inferior optic radiations (Meyer\u0027s loop) course through the anterior temporal lobe and injury causes contralateral superior quadrantanopia","Anterior temporal lobectomy is a surgical treatment option for drug-resistant temporal lobe epilepsy","Visual field deficits after temporal lobe surgery occur in up to 40% of patients"],"references":["Blumenfeld H. Neuroanatomy through clinical cases. 2010. p. 460-490.","Yogarajah M, Focke NK, Bonelli S, Cercignani M, Acheson J, Parker GJ. Defining Meyer\u0027s loop-temporal lobe resections, visual field deficits and diffusion tensor tractography. Brain. 2009 Jun;132(Pt 6):1656-68. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2685925/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60933"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1931"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"1931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/1931"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b6133281-9072-45ad-8157-c5101afe9e4f.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/b6133281-9072-45ad-8157-c5101afe9e4f.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":370,"height":326}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60933"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T20:00:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-12T09:47:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75423"}}},"meta":{"canDel